A ‘blob’ of warm water is sitting in the Pacific Ocean from Alaska to Mexico . 
  University of Washington study says it could be responsible for droughts in the West coast of the US . 
  It has extended 1,000 miles (1,600km) offshore and could herald a warmer summer . 
  California is experiencing its worst ever drought while the East is in cold weather . 
  A high-pressure ridge could be trapping heat in the water . 
  It is also having an effect on marine life . 
 